Fruit abortion may occur. On older fruits, dark leathery sunken spots develop at the point of attachment to the stem. 
Control: Use copper fungicides, seed treatment and crop rotation.
Bacterial wilt 
It’s characterised by rapid wilting of the plant (more rapid than fusarium wilt). If cut across the stem, a slimy substance oozes out and the pith may be dark or water-soaked in appearance.
Pathogen is soil-borne but may also be introduced through irrigation water and trash. Control: Rotation (4-5 years), rouging and field hygiene.
Pests 
Cutworms
They attack only seedlings by cutting off the stems at or just below the soil surface.
Control: Cultivation to disturb the places they spend during dry periods, use of insecticides and use of cutworm collars.
Green peach aphids
They are usually light green and soft-bodied. They cluster on leaf undersides or on stems. Aphids excrete a sticky liquid called honeydew, which creates spots on foliage.
A black fungus, sooty mould, may then grow on the honeydew. Severe infestations can cause wilting, stunting, curly and leaf distortion. Control is by use of predators to feed on the aphids and use of insecticides.
Leafhoppers
Leafhoppers are small, sap-sacking insects. Attacked capsicums have the tips of leaves turning yellow to brown and becoming brittle. Control can be achieved by removal of infested plants or parts immediately.



