Recipe for marmalade
Dear Faith Ndungi, I was inspired by your marmalade recipe and have two questions. How much marmalade does one get from your recipe? I don't have glass jars, can I use recycled screw top containers?Graham Girvan, Kimilili
If the marmalade is to be used in a few weeks, it should be covered with a well-fitting lid and kept in a cool place or in a refrigerator.
Marmalades to be kept for longer periods should be processed in a boiling water bath, sealed with melted wax, cooled, labelled and then stored in a cool dry place.
The jars used should be cleaned and sterilised in boiling water for at least 10 minutes. The containers must be submerged in the boiling water.
After this, they are kept hot either in a slow oven or left in the sterilisation water on top of low heat until the marmalade is ready.
Glass jars are the most preferred. In the case of a recycled container, it should be able to withstand the sterilisation and processing boiling water as well as oven heat.
Most of the recipes outlined in the November 21 article are for small-scale or household-level production.
They produce from one to three kilos of marmalade, which can he held by two to six 500ml jars of marmalade respectively. For large production, the recipe can be increased to suit mass production.



